checklist.title: Autologon Passwords
checklist.content:
What is Autologon ?

Instead of waiting for a user to enter their name and password, Windows uses the credentials you enter with Autologon, which are encrypted in the Registry, to log on the specified user automatically.


What is Vulnerability ?

Not in all OS it is stores password as encypted and as its encrypted in some cases its possible to decrypt those too.


Adding Vulnerability in your machine.

	Open registory editor [by pressing windows+r and type regedit and press enter ]





GOTO HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\Currentversion\Winlogon
and add DefaultUsername & Default Password Entry same as below.[Use Your own Username Passwords]



Restart Your System and You will  Notice That its logged in Autometically


Finding & Exploiting Vulnerability 


You Must have User level Accsess



  • Using Powershell 
Get-ItemProperty -Path "HKLM:SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Winlogon" |select DefaultP
assword,DefaultUserName


  • Using cmd.exe 
reg query "HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\Currentversion\Winlogon" |findstr /i "DefaultUserName DefaultPassword"


Login To High privilege User When You Have Credentials



  • Using PowerShell
$username = 'user'
$password = 'password'

$securePassword = ConvertTo-SecureString $password -AsPlainText -Force
$credential = New-Object System.Management.Automation.PSCredential $username, $securePassword
Start-Process <Your Backdoor File> -Credential $credential



  • Using CMD [Require TTY]
runas /user:<localmachinename>\<username> cmd


  • Remote Services

If WinRm Or RDP is Running [port 5985/5986 or 3389 is open]

evil-winrm 


  WINRM[5985/5986]
evil-winrm -i <IP Of Target> -u <Username> -p <Passwords> [if 5986 add -ssl arg ]



RDP[3389]
rdesktop -u <Username> -p <Password> <target_IP>

checklist.title: Insecure Service Permission
checklist.content:
What is Service in windows ?

Aserviceis a small program that usually starts when theWindowsoperating system loads. You won't normally interact withserviceslike you do with regular programs because they run in the background (you don't see them) and don't provide a normal user interface [Same As linux Cron Jobs]


What Is Permision Of Service ?

Services Has Permisions that if Users can stop service or modify service properties setted in registry


What Is Vulnerability ?

If Users Can modify Services properties Attacker can modify Binpath pointing to his malware, So whenever Service tries to execute program as binpath is changed it will execute Malware instead of Offical Program with Higher privilege .


What is Binpath ?

Its an Argument Which stores executable for services.


Adding Vulnerability in your machine.


  • Open Registy editoy And go to HKLM\System\CurrentControlSet\services\
  • Here You Will Find All Services Installed.
  • Right Click on any service Click on Permission And Allow Users to Have full Control


  • Done

Finding Vulnerability 


Using PowerShell
Get-Acl HKLM:\System\CurrentControlSet\services\* | Format-List * |findstr /i "PSPATH Users <Username>"
Example.
Get-Acl HKLM:\System\CurrentControlSet\services\*|Format-List * |findstr /i "PSPath USERS Elliot" //for finding all services 
Get-Acl HKLM:\System\CurrentControlSet\services\<vulnerable Service>\|Format-List * |findstr /i "PSPath USERS Elliot"
Get-Acl HKLM:\System\CurrentControlSet\services\wampapache64\|Format-List * |findstr /i "PSPath USERS Elliot"
PSPath         : Microsoft.PowerShell.Core\Registry::HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\services\wampapache64\
AccessToString     : BUILTIN\Users Allow FullControl
             BUILTIN\Users Allow ReadKey
             BUILTIN\Users Allow -2147483648
PS C:\Users\Administrator>

Using CMD
sc.exe query //to get services list
sc.exe sdshow <service name>
                                      //accesschk.exe can be used here

checklist.title: Unquoted Service PATH
checklist.content:
What is Service in windows ?

Aserviceis a small program that usually starts when theWindowsoperating system loads. You won't normally interact withserviceslike you do with regular programs because they run in the background (you don't see them) and don't provide a normal user interface [Same As linux Cron Jobs]


What does it means by quoted Service and Unquoted Sevice ?

BinPath Of Service Is inside ""[quotes] that means its quoted if its not quoted that means Unquoted.


What Is Vlnerability here ?

If Service's Binpath values are not in quotes it is possible to execute our malware when that service loads.


how ?

Windows automaticaly adds .exe at the and of any cmd if we havent specified


like if i type icacls.exe or icacls only both will works

it checks if file ends with exe or not, if not it will add it automatically.


So if i used bipath values inside "" than it will execute that whole path+binay but its not that then,it will try to find binary

example.

c:\program files (x86)\a subfolder\b subfolder\binary.exe //binpath values 
in this case windows wil ty to find 
c:\program.exe at first as space are there if its not there it will move to  
c:\program files.exe if its not there thn further as below 
c:\program files (x86)\a.exe
c:\program files (x86)\a subfolder\b.exe
c:\program files (x86)\a subfolder\b subfolder\binary.exe

so if user has write perm of any of these location i can execute my malware here

checklist.title: Token Impersonation
checklist.content:
What it is ?

One of the techniques of token manipulation is creating a new process with a token "stolen" from another process. This is when a token of an already existing access token present in one of the running processes on the victim host, is retrieved, duplicated and then used for creating a new process, making the new process assume the privileges of that stolen token.


What Is Require For Labs ?



  • Windows 10 < 1809 OR Windows Server < 2019
  • Access To Target With Service Account [Ex. IIS user (iis iusr)]
  • User Must Have SeImpersonatePrivilege OR SeAssignPrimaryToken Privilege [Check with Whoami /priv] [Most Service Accound Has That Privilege]


What Is SeImpersonatePrivilege ?

1:- "Impersonate a client after authentication"	
2:- "Token can be impersonated by a thread through various API calls  SetThreadToken(), ImpersonateLoggedOnUser()  "
3:- "Token can be impersonated by a process through CreateProcessWithToken()  API call which relies on the Secondary Logon Service"


What is SeAssignPrimaryToken ?

1:- "Assign the primary token of a process"
2:- "Token can be impersonated by a process through CreateProcessAsUser() call"
3:- "Privilege also available in the standard shell (medium IL)"


How can we obtain privileged tokens to impersonate them?

1:- "Creating a  named pipe, forcing a privileged process to write to it and then calling  ImpersonateNamedPipeClient()  in order to obtain the privileged threads token"
2:- "Establishing a Security Context -AcceptSecurityContext() -with a specific SSP (NTLM) in a localhost                 authentication and acquiring a token of the privileged user -QuerySecurityContextToken() "
3:- "DCOM/RPC callbacks (CoImpersonateClient(), RpcImpersonateClient()) "


Rotten Potato the killer exploit to abuse from these privileges 


  • "Local DCOM DCE/RPC connections can be reflected back to a listening TCP socket allowing access to a n NTLM authentication challenge for LocalSystemuser which can be replayed to the local DCOM activation service to elevate privileges" -James Forshaw 
  • Exploit & great POC here -Stephen Breen, Chris Mallz


From Rotten Potato To Juicy Potato

  1. Rotten Potato and its standalone variants leverages the privilege escalation chain based on BITS service having the MiTMlistener on 127.0.0.1:6666 and when you have SeImpersonateor SeAssignPrimaryTokenprivileges.
  2. During a Windows Desktop hardening review Creators friend Giuseppe found a weak service configuration and gained access as Network Service but BITS was not accessible and port 6666 was firewalled 
  3. So they decided together to weaponizeRotten Potato making:


Why Specific Windows Versions ?

Of cource Wondows Patched Their OS after that.
